The  instruction decrements the content of a register by 1, and sets the  in the CPU if the new value of the register is zero. (If youâ€™re not familiar with jumps and flags in Assembly, hereâ€™s a good explainer for you).Next,  performs the byte-level move from  to .Then, we jump to the start of the loop if the  has not been set.Here are the results from this: Now  is more like what I expected â€” we start out competitive with  for small strings, and then get worse and worse as the input grows bigger. By the time we get to 256 bytes of input,  is more than 20x slower than . Itâ€™s clear, then, that  is doing some heavy optimisations in the processor to allow us keep up with .Itâ€™s clear that  is at least within the range of  for large strings, so weâ€™ll focus our optimisation efforts on making sure that we can keep up with  for smaller strings, and progressively optimise on the way up.Much of the improvement for small strings will center around a single concept â€” modern CPUs are heavily optimised to transfer blocks of data, rather single bytes at a time. This is even observable from the results; even though larger string sizes equate to more data being moved, there isnâ€™t a linear scale up in the execution time of the different implementations.With that in mind, here is our revised implementation:global asmcpy
section .text
asmcpy:
    cmp rdx, 4
    jae .four
    mov rcx, rdx
    cld

.min:
    dec rdx
    movsb
    jne .min
    sub rdi, rcx
    mov rax, rdi
    ret


.four:
    cmp rdx, 8
    jae .eight
    mov ecx, [rsi + rdx*1 - 4]
    mov [rdi + rdx*1 - 4], ecx
    movsd
    sub rdi, 4
    mov rax, rdi
    ret

.eight:
    cmp rdx, 16
    jae .xmm
    mov rcx, [rsi + rdx*1 - 8]
    mov [rdi + rdx * 1 - 8], rcx
    movsq
    sub rdi, 8
    mov rax, rdi
    ret
Okay, we already know that the  loop is fine for small pieces of data, so weâ€™ll leave that.First, we have separate blocks for different input ranges. This is done to make sure that small strings only result in two copies at maximum. Control flow in Assembly is implemented by  between blocks based on different conditions.Take the , for example: first, we compare (the count) with 4 and jump if the count is  to 4. We accomplish this using the  and  instructions.  takes two operands and performs performs integer subtraction between them (i.e a - b), but it also sets the  register based on the result. If you are unfamiliar with how control flow works at the CPU level, Iâ€™d recommend this brief write-up.Thereâ€™s an interesting trick here: Whenever we have data that straddles two native word sizes, i.e sizes between 4 and 8, or 8 and 16, we do two native copies and align them.While we do â€œover-copyâ€ a single element, itâ€™s worth it for the efficiency of doing word-multiple copies.mov ecx, [rsi + rdx*1 - 4]
